  <front>
   <head>The WIDOWER's COURTSHIP.</head>
  </front>
  <body>
   <lg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="poem">
    <lg n="1" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="1" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">a doleful widower,</l>
     <l n="2" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">Full eighteen weeks had been,</l>
     <l n="3" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">When he, to meet the milk-maid Nell,</l>
     <l n="4" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">Came smiling o'er the green.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="2" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="5" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Blithe as a lad of seventeen,</l>
     <l n="6" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">He thus accosted Nell;</l>
     <l n="7" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Give me your pail, I'll carry it</l>
     <l n="8" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">For you, if you think well.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="3" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="9" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Says Nell, indeed my milking-pail</l>
     <l n="10" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">You shall not touch, I vow;</l>
     <l n="11" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">I've carried it myself before,</l>
     <l n="12" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">And I can carry it now.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="4" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="13" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">So side by side they walk'd a-while,</l>
     <l n="14" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">Then he at last did say;</l>
     <l n="15" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">My inclination is to come</l>
     <l n="16" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">And see you, if I may.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="5" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="17" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Nell understood his meaning well,</l>
     <l n="18" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">And briskly answer'd she;</l>
     <l n="19" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">You may see me at any time,</l>
     <l n="20" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">If you look where I be.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="6" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="21" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Says he, but hear me yet a-while,</l>
     <l n="22" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">I've something more to tell;</l>
     <l n="23" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">I gladly wou'd a sweetheart be</l>
     <l n="24" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">Unto you, Mistress Nell.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="7" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="25" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">A sweetheart I don't want, says Nell,</l>
     <l n="26" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">Kind Sir, and if you do,</l>
     <l n="27" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Another you may seek, for I</l>
     <l n="28" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">Am not the lass for you.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="8" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="29" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">When she had made him this reply,</l>
     <l n="30" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">He'd nothing more to say</l>
     <l n="31" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">But — Nelly, a good night to you,</l>
     <l n="32" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">And homeward went his way.</l>
    </lg>
   </lg>
  </body>
